				\begin{document}$$P_3 = {\int}_k {\kern 1pt} p_3(k){\mathrm{e}}^{j(kx - 2\rm{\pi}f_0t)}{\rm{d}}k$$\end{document}P3=∫kp3(k)ej(kx-2πf0t)dk. The amplitudes p1(k), p2(k′) and p3(k) are derived in later sections as transmission coefficients of filter layers and grating layers. The grating will also generate other higher odd order diffractions (3th order, 5th order, …). Then the filter layer in the receiver will perform post-filtering for the waves with wave number |k| ∈ [kG − k0, kG] or [kG, kG + k0] in the first order diffraction. Other higher-order diffractions are all attenuated after passing through the filter layer at the receiver. In order to prevent the overlapping of +1st and −1st diffraction orders of the grating layer, the wavenumber bands of the wave after passing through the filter layer cannot locate in [kG − k0, kG] and [kG, kG + k0] simultaneously. By changing the geometric parameters, the filtering band of the filter layer and the grating constant kG of the grating layer can be adjusted to different locations in the spatial spectrum. Thus we can separately project the bands |k| ∈ [nk0, (n + 1)k0], n = 1, 2, 3, 4, … N, to the far-field, as shown in Fig. 1b. The received signals are denoted by P3n respectively. The propagating waves with |k| ∈ [0, k0], denoted by P30, will be obtained by wave propagating through an empty waveguide without transmitter/receiver. The final image can be formed in two ways. One way is summing up all the components together \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
